* 2022 Aug 19: version 1.8

	Added support for hjkl navigation. Additionally, the key command
	to view the list of character blocks has been moved to ^B. Thanks
	to Štěpán Němec for patches and feedback.

* 2022 Aug 15: version 1.7

	This release just fixes some errors in the documentation that got
	missed in 1.6. Thanks to Štěpán Němec for catching these as well.
	This is also the first release that includes this file.

* 2022 Aug 14: version 1.6

	The main change in this version is the addition of a search
	command to the list of character blocks. (There are over 300
	blocks, so this feature was overdue.)

	Additionally, the program no longer has a set default layout of
	two columns, but instead selects a comfortable default based on
	the terminal width.

	This version cleans up some errors in the code, including a fix
	for the incomplete bug fix done in 1.4. Some of the more slapdash
	aspects of the build process have been polished. Most importantly,
	the python scripts used in the build process now work properly
	with python 3.x.

	Finally, there are fixes for numerous minor errors in both the
	comments and the documentation.

	Nearly every improvement in this version is due, either in whole
	or in part, to contributions from Štěpán Němec.

* 2022 Jan 31: version 1.5

	The "input mode" feature has been added, in which ubrowse becomes
	a filter and verbosely describes each character on stdin. Useful
	for quickly identifying an odd character when you don't need the
	full UI experience.

	Since ubrowse now has some non-obvious features, a man page has
	finally been added to the distribution.

* 2019 Oct 11: version 1.4

	The "I" command was added to view character info. It feels a
	little klugey, but I dislike having to switch to another program
	like gucharmap just to get this information.

	This release also has many miscellaneous tweaks and cleanups,
	including a fix for a segfault in the search UI.

* 2017 Nov 11: version 1.3

	First public release. (This tool was originally written as a
	learning exercise in using Unicode with ncurses. However, I find
	myself frequently making use of it as a tool, so it seems
	generally useful than I originally realized.)
